  "prompt": "What happens if your heart beats too fast?",
  "response": "When your heart beats too fast (a condition called tachycardia), several potential issues can occur:\n\n1. Short-term symptoms:\n- Chest pain or discomfort\n- Shortness of breath\n- Dizziness\n- Lightheadedness\n- Rapid pulse\n- Fainting\n- Anxiety\n\n2. Potential health risks:\n- Reduced blood flow to organs\n- Decreased oxygen supply\n- Increased strain on the heart\n- Risk of heart failure\n- Potential blood clot formation\n- Risk of stroke\n\n3. Specific conditions causing fast heart rate:\n- Atrial fibrillation\n- Supraventricular tachycardia\n- Ventricular tachycardia\n- Anxiety or stress\n- Fever\n- Dehydration\n- Certain medications\n- Thyroid problems\n\n4. Treatment options:\n- Medication\n- Cardioversion\n- Catheter ablation\n- Lifestyle changes\n- Managing underlying conditions\n\nIf you experience persistent rapid heartbeat, it's important to consult a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment.",
